{"cursor":"8305","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Italian comune\n| name = Norcia official_name = Comune di Norcia native_name = image_skyline =\n| Norcia-panorama.jpg imagesize = image_alt = image_caption = image_shield =\n| shield_alt = image_map = map_alt = map_caption = pushpin_label_position =\n| pushpin_map_alt = latd = 42 |latm = 48 |lats = |latNS = N longd = 13 |longm =\n| 06 |longs = |longEW = E coordinates_type = coordinates_display =\n| coordinates_footnotes = region = Umbria province = Perugia (PG) frazioni = see\n| list mayor_party = mayor = Gian Paolo Stefanelli area_footnotes =\n| area_total_km2 = 274 population_footnotes = population_total = 4695\n| population_as_of = pop_density_footnotes = population_demonym = Nursini\n| elevation_footnotes = elevation_m = 604 twin1 = twin1_country = saint = St.\n| Benedict day = March 21, July 11 postal_code = 06046 area_code = 0743 website\n| = footnotes =\n}}\n\n\n'Norcia', traditionally known in English by its Latin name of 'Nursia', is a\ntown and commune in the province of Perugia (Italy) in southeastern Umbria.\nUnlike many ancient towns, it is located in a wide plain abutting the Monti\nSibillini, a subrange of the Apennines with some of its highest peaks, near the\nSordo River, a small stream that eventually flows into the Nera. The town is\npopularly associated with the Valnerina (the valley of that river).\n\nThe area is known for its air and scenery, and is a base for mountaineering and\nhiking. It is also widely known for hunting, especially of the wild boar, and\nfor sausages and ham made from wild boar and pork. Such products have been named\nafter Norcia; in Italian, they are called norcineria.\n","linknr":268,"url":"Norcia","recorded":1371244030,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Norcia&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Norcia&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licen